Ecological Behaviour Analysis in Malaysia

Yeo Xiu Juan

24 April 2022

Problem Statement

Sustainability literacy is about demonstrating ones awareness of sustainability and its complex relationships in the environment and society. It is about possessing the necessary information, knowledge, skills and mindsets that allow individuals to commit, formulate and communicate sustainable solutions through multidisciplinary approaches.

Malaysia ranked 132nd in the Global Sustainability index.The country was also a global leader in plastic manufacturing.One of the key challenge the country faced was plastic pollution. Plastic waste contain toxic chemical that can seriously impair health.

Therefore, the purpose of this study will analyse Malaysians literacy towards sustainability and which factor impair them from saving the planet.

What will be investigated ?

  1. Do gender make a difference when come to environmental awareness?

  2. Do income drive away sustainability ?

Rename gender from Original Data : 1 = Male , 2 = Female

Ordinary Least squares

4 models will be conducted to address malaysians ecological awareness and attitude towards sustainability .

Model 1 & 2 : Green Attitude X Income

Model 1 Main Effect

$$ \[\begin{eqnarray} \widehat{greenbehaviour} = intercept + b_1greenaAtitude + b_2Age + b_3Education+ b_4Income + b_5Ethicity + b_6female + \epsilon\\ \end{eqnarray}\] $$ Our key investigation lies in the next model, in which we regressed income and green decision orientations, along with interaction terms, onto Green Behaviour(model2).

Model 2 Interaction model

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \widehat{greenbehaviour} = intercept + b_1greenaAtitude + b_2Age + b_3Education+ b_4Income + b_5Ethicity + b_6female + \\ + b_7female \times green attitude + b_8age\times green attitude + b_9education \times green attitude + b_10Ethnicity \times green attitude + \epsilon \end{eqnarray} \]

Interpretation for Model 2 Green Attitude X Income

Based on the hypothesis testing ,after setting the confidence interval ,the three income level is overlapping and it shows that there is no significance in terms of income level when comes to green attitude. Even through from the reality, many could see that higher social consumer group may have greater perception of green attitude Certainty, the ability to purchase green products are on the higher price than non-green products, but minimal effort such as making use of the daily resources could protect the the environment.

Green attitude and income level is based on observational study,leading to correlation causation in limitations and future directions.

Model 3 & 4 : Green Seeking X Gender

Centered_data_m2 <- green_data %>% 
    mutate_at(vars(-c(green_behaviour,female)
    ), 
    ~(. - mean(., na.rm = T)
    )
    )

$$ \[\begin{eqnarray} \widehat{greenbehaviour } = intercept + b_1greenseeking + b_2Age + b_3Education+ b_4Income + b_5Ethicity + b_6Education + b_7female + b_8 green concern + \epsilon \end{eqnarray}\]

\[ \]

\[\begin{eqnarray} \widehat{greenbehaviour } = intercept + b_1greenseeking + b_2Age + b_3Education+ b_4Income + b_5Ethicity + b_6Education + b_7female + b_8 green concern + \\ +b_9 Ethnicity \times green seeking + b_10 Income \times green seeking + b_11 Education \times green seeking + b_12 Age \times green seeking + b_13 female \times green seeking + +b_14 green concern + \epsilon \end{eqnarray}\] $$

model3 <- Centered_data_m2 %>% 
    lm(formula =    green_behaviour ~ green_seeking + Age + Ethnicity + Income + Education + female + green_concern,
       data = .)
model4 <- Centered_data_m2 %>% 
    lm(formula = green_behaviour ~ green_seeking *(Ethnicity + Income + Education  + Age + female)+ green_concern,
       data = .)

model4_WO_center <- green_data %>%

       data = .)

Interpretation for Model 4

Although,many studies have shown that many have the misconception of greenness is femininity.Men are often less eco-friendly than women due to fear of being teased by their sexual preference.

From the linear graph, female slope was higher than male but after setting the confidence interval,Male and female is overlapping ,there is no significance between gender when it comes to seeking for greener products.We would therefore, reject the hypothesis.

The relationships between green seeking and gender is based on observational study,leading to correlations, not causations.

Limitations and Future Directions

The data size was only from 375 respondent which is difficult to find the significant relationships. The purpose of this project was to provide a exploration on bridging the eco gender gap and the social class groups seeking for green environment.
